sec.p:
Transient absorption spectroscopy is a well-established method to study dynamic processes in a wide range of solar energy conversion materials. Time-resolved spectroscopy as we know it today was developed in the 1950s and early 1960s as flash photolysis and relaxation methods, a development that culminated with the Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1967 to Porter, Norrish, and Eigen [11]. The fundamental idea of the method is to use a pulsed excitation source, often denoted as pump source, to excite a sample from the ground to the excited state. The optical absorption of the excited state or other photogenerated intermediates is then spectroscopically monitored by a probe beam at certain time delay after its generation through a second excitation source. In particular, the probe beam intensity before I0(λ)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
