In both classical and dispersive kinetic models, an underlying assumption is that charge carrier concentration [c]\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$[c]$$\end{document} is a continuous real-valued function of time. However, in nanocrystalline materials, each particle acts as a micro-reactor where the number of photogenerated charge carriers is at most a couple hundred, and thus [c]\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$[c]$$\end{document} is integer-valued. As an example, if 10 electron–hole pairs were generated in 100 particles, the classical view would wrongly assume that all particles would be populated with 0.1 pairs. The correct description of 90% empty particles and 10% particles with one electron–hole pair (neglecting the small number of particles populated with two or more pairs) thus calls for stochastic kinetics to be employed.

Another good example of stochastic treatments is that by Grela and Colussi, who performed numerical modeling of electron–hole recombination (and reactive processes) on the surface of colloidal TiO2 particles [121]. In this simple but elegant model, the surface is modeled as a square 2D periodic lattice, and electron and holes are initially generated at random positions. Moreover, holes perform a random walk on the surface, while electrons are fixed (thus assuming that they are deeply trapped in colloidal TiO2). Under these conditions, recombination in particles with multiple pairs follows dispersive second-order kinetics, with the rate coefficient approaching a t-1/2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${t}^{-1/2}$$\end{document} dependence. This behavior is explained by the inhomogeneity in the initial distribution of charge carriers on the surface: while electron and hole pairs generated at close positions promptly recombine, those farther apart survive for longer times. Electron–hole pairs with very long lifetimes are then responsible for the “baseline” behavior previously mentioned (Eq. (4)). Under low average numbers of photogenerated electron–hole per particle, the simulations correctly reproduce the experimentally observed [42] mono-exponential decays.
